0.body: This book describes the major phonological, orthographic, syntactic, and semantic properties of Najan, my first and so far only conlang. Najan is an a priori , analytic, isolating conlang featuring perfectly phonemic orthography, an unambiguous context-free grammar, and pronoun binding and quantification rules inspired by first-order logic. The Najan name for Najan is kʊv naj vɪx [kʰʊv näʒ vɪɾ̥ʰ]. I have no formal linguistic training, so the language is not very naturalistic or elaborate as far as conlangs go. Nevertheless, it's been a joy to work on, and I'm happy with how it has evolved and am excited to share it with others. Soli Deo gloria.
0.title: Introduction

1.body: Stress falls on the first syllable of a word. However, stress never distinguishes words and can be altered for emphasis. Najan is stress-timed. Consonants Bilabial Labio-dental Dental Alveolar Post-alveolar Palatal Velar Nasal m n ŋ Plosive pʰ b tʰ d kʰ g Affricate t̪͡θʰ d̪͡ð t͡sʰ d͡z t̠͡ʃʰ d̠͡ʒ kxʰ gɣ Fricative f v θ ð s z ʃ ʒ x ɣ Approximant l j w [1] Tap ɾ̥ʰ ɾ Lateral affricate t͡ɬ d͡ɮ Lateral fricative (ɬ) (ɮ) Specifically, labial-velar Across word boundaries, consonants with the same point of articulation are geminated. For instance, a word-final k ⟨k⟩ followed by a word-initial g ⟨g⟩ would be pronounced [k:g] (note the lack of the usual aspiration) since both are velar. In contrast, the ⟨k⟩ in ⟨-k t-⟩ is aspirated since ⟨t⟩ is alveolar. Within a word, a plosive-fricative cluster with a single point of articulation becomes an affricate. t ⟨t⟩ and d ⟨d⟩, which normally denote alveolar plosives, shift their point of articulation before dental or post-alveolar fricatives to align with the fricative. The clusters tl ⟨tl⟩ and dl ⟨dl⟩ become the lateral affricates [t͡ɬ] and [d͡ɮ], respectively. Similarly, but only in some dialects, sl ⟨sl⟩ and zl ⟨zl⟩ become the lateral fricatives [ɬ] and [ɮ]. 1.title: Phonology

10.body: Najan marks case using prepositions, in both prepositional phrases acting as arguments to a verb and in stativized verb phrases using the particle vʊ ⟨vʊ⟩. Case Gloss Preposition Subjective sʙᴊ ŋɪ ⟨ŋɪ⟩ Genitive ɢᴇɴ qa ⟨qa⟩ Agentive ᴀ ci ⟨ci⟩ Causal ᴄᴀᴜs slo ⟨slo⟩ Patientive ᴘ rʊ ⟨rʊ⟩ Instrumental ɪɴs θla ⟨θla⟩ Partitive ᴘᴛᴠ bo ⟨bo⟩ Locative ʟᴏᴄ lɪ ⟨lɪ⟩ Lative ʟᴀᴛ we ⟨we⟩ Ablative ᴀʙʟ xun ⟨xun⟩ Perlative ᴘᴇʀ zij ⟨zij⟩ Resultative ʀᴇs tce ⟨tce⟩ Identical ɪᴅᴇɴᴛ kʊv ⟨kʊv⟩ Semblative sᴇᴍʙʟ kɪ ⟨kɪ⟩ Within a stative verb phrase, a subject (sʙᴊ) is something that is in that state. A stative verb phrase may also take a genitive (ɢᴇɴ) argument, which relates that argument to the subject according to the semantics of the verb. The genitive preposition qa ⟨qa⟩ means "with respect to", "with regard to", or "in relation to". jeqavɪθŋɪkozimjeqavɪθŋɪkozimɪɴᴅɢᴇɴexistsʙᴊIwant“I want to exist.” The role of the genitive case in Najan is relatively narrow, reserved for abstract relations where no other case applies. For example, the genitive is distinct from the locative and partitive cases. An agent (ᴀ) of a dynamic verb phrase is an animate, voluntary cause of the action. A patient (ᴘ) is something that is acted upon or undergoes change as a result of the action. jecikorʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehjecikorʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehɪɴᴅᴀIᴘthesuch-thatbe-sandsᴛᴀᴛʀᴇsfortifyᴘғᴠdestroy“I destroyed the sand castle (intentionally).” In contrast to an agent, a cause (ᴄᴀᴜs) is involuntary. jeslokorʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehjeslokorʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehɪɴᴅᴄᴀᴜsIᴘthesuch-thatbe-sandsᴛᴀᴛʀᴇsfortifyᴘғᴠdestroy“I destroyed the sand castle (unintentionally).” A cause can also be inanimate. jeslogivuculrʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehjeslogivuculrʊginʊganθvʊtcekwonθeflehɪɴᴅᴄᴀᴜstheseaᴘthesuch-thatbe-sandsᴛᴀᴛʀᴇsfortifyᴘғᴠdestroy“The sea destroyed the sand castle.” The lative (ʟᴀᴛ) case is used for any kind of action to or towards something, in space or time. jewetocikoθezenjewetocikoθezenɪɴᴅʟᴀᴛyouᴀIᴘғᴠgive“I gave [it] to you.” The semblative (sᴇᴍʙʟ) case marks something the verb is similar to. The semblative particle kɪ ⟨kɪ⟩ means "as", "like", or "in the manner of". honkɪðulecpɪfhonkɪðulecpɪfɢɴᴏsᴇᴍʙʟɢɴʀwatersoothe“[It] soothes like water.”
10.title: Case

11.body: Najan has two first-person plural pronouns, distinguished by clusivity. The inclusive pronoun djof ⟨djof⟩ includes the speaker, those addressed, and possibly one or more third-person referents. The exclusive pronoun jal ⟨jal⟩ includes the speaker and at least one third person but excludes those addressed. First-person Pronouns Singular Plural inclusive Plural exclusive ko ⟨ko⟩ djof ⟨djof⟩ jal ⟨jal⟩ Second-person Pronouns Singular Plural to ⟨to⟩ ŋak ⟨ŋak⟩ The interrogative pronoun velk ⟨velk⟩ stands for something unknown and is essential to the formation of interrogative sentences, where it indicates any missing information that the asker wishes to know.
11.title: Pronouns

12.body: The assignable pronouns jow ⟨jow⟩, með ⟨með⟩, paŋ ⟨paŋ⟩, and tsut ⟨tsut⟩ have no fixed properties, such as person, number, or gender. They can be bound (or rebound) to any unquantified noun phrase, via determiner phrases.
12.title: Assignable Pronouns

13.body: A determiner phrase consists of a determiner, an optional pronoun to bind, and a stative verb phrase complement. The phrase signifies some entity such that the complement holds true with that entity as the subject. Najan has just four determiners: Determiner Type Translation za ⟨za⟩ Indefinite "a"/"an" gi ⟨gi⟩ Definite "the" su ⟨su⟩ Distributive "each"/"every" ðu ⟨ðu⟩ Generic "in general" The indefinite determiner za ⟨za⟩ introduces a new specific instance of the complement. It corresponds to existential quantification in logic. jezalakcɪŋjezalakcɪŋɪɴᴅabirdsee“A bird is being seen.” The definite determiner gi ⟨gi⟩ refers to a known instance of the complement. The referent should be unique (e.g. a proper noun) or otherwise obvious from context. There is only one entity that is the sun: jecigiθxɪlfiqjecigiθxɪlfiqɪɴᴅᴀthesunshine“The sun is shining.” We can express a demonstrative ("this" or "that") by modifying the complement of a definite determiner with nʊ tlɪ ⟨nʊ tlɪ⟩ ("here") or nʊ dwa ⟨nʊ dwa⟩ ("there"). The distributive determiner su ⟨su⟩ expresses that the clauses containing the determiner phrase (and its pronoun, if any) hold true for each instance of the complement. It corresponds to universal quantification in logic. jerʊsuvɪxfxecayjerʊsuvɪxfxecayɪɴᴅᴘeachlanguageʜᴀʙchange“Every language changes.” The generic determiner ðu ⟨ðu⟩ refers to the complement in a general, nonspecific sense. It's often used with the gnomic aspect . This determiner doesn't map cleanly to any one determiner in English; for instance, "a man's gotta eat", "cats are cute", and "the giraffe is an African species" all have a generic subject. jeŋɪkoðudwavkemjeŋɪkoðudwavkemɪɴᴅsʙᴊIɢɴʀbooklike“I like books.” In English, the indefinite articles "a" and "an" do not encode specificity. For instance, "I'm looking for a book" could mean I have or don't have a specific book in mind. In Najan, the indefinite determiner is always specific: jeŋɪkozadwavmoθjeŋɪkozadwavmoθɪɴᴅsʙᴊIabookneed“I need a (particular) book.” The generic determiner is always nonspecific. jeŋɪkoðudwavmoθjeŋɪkoðudwavmoθɪɴᴅsʙᴊIɢɴʀbookneed“I need a book (any book).”

13.title: Determiner Phrases

14.body: Binding a pronoun in a determiner phrase allows referring back to it in a concise and unambiguous way. jecigipaŋdzaðrʊpaŋθekhɪtcjecigipaŋdzaðrʊpaŋθekhɪtcɪɴᴅᴀtheitchildᴘitᴘғᴠhurt“The child hurt itself.”
14.breadcrumbs: Noun Phrases » Determiner Phrases » Pronoun Binding
14.title: Pronoun Binding

15.body: We have to be careful about the order of arguments when distributive determiners and indefinite determiners are both present since they are not commutative with each other. It's true that every human has a human mother: jeqasuðapŋɪzaðapθafjeqasuðapŋɪzaðapθafɪɴᴅɢᴇɴeachhumansʙᴊahumanmother“Every human is mothered by a human.” It is however not true that all humans share a single universal mother: jeŋɪzaðapqasuðapθafjeŋɪzaðapqasuðapθafɪɴᴅsʙᴊahumanɢᴇɴeachhumanmother“There is a human that is mother to every human.”
15.breadcrumbs: Noun Phrases » Determiner Phrases » Ordering Determiner Phrases
15.title: Ordering Determiner Phrases

16.body: A quotation begins and ends with the particle tca ⟨tca⟩ and functions as a noun signifying the contained words themselves. The particle tsa ⟨tsa⟩ is used within a quotation just before tca ⟨tca⟩ or another tsa ⟨tsa⟩ to indicate that the second particle should be interpreted as part of the quotation, not as a particle within the sentence containing the quotation. Note: Determiner phrases within quotations cannot affect the bindings of surrounding pronouns. Assignable pronouns contained in a quotation may have completely different referents than in the surrounding context—or even none at all, when using a quotation to talk about the pronouns themselves.
16.title: Quotation

Each grapheme name begins with the grapheme itself. Since Najan is perfectly phonemic, this table also represents all the Najan phonemes. Note however, that these phonemes are not always pronounced exactly as the example phones, due to the allophonic variations described in Phonology . The Najan Alphabet k ⟨kθat⟩ [kʰ] g ⟨glew⟩ [g] t ⟨tedð⟩ [tʰ] d ⟨dewr⟩ [d] p ⟨pul⟩ [pʰ] b ⟨byas⟩ [b] h ⟨hak⟩ [x] q ⟨qot⟩ [ɣ] s ⟨sɪj⟩ [s] z ⟨zaw⟩ [z] f ⟨foj⟩ [f] v ⟨vis⟩ [v] θ ⟨θatc⟩ [θ] ð ⟨ðʊc⟩ [ð] c ⟨ceŋ⟩ [ʃ] j ⟨jok⟩ [ʒ] x ⟨xotθ⟩ [ɾ̥ʰ] r ⟨rayŋ⟩ [ɾ] ŋ ⟨ŋʊp⟩ [ŋ] n ⟨nekθ⟩ [n] m ⟨muts⟩ [m] y ⟨yan⟩ [j] l ⟨lɪn⟩ [l] w ⟨woð⟩ [w] ʊ ⟨ʊlf⟩ [ʊ] a ⟨adz⟩ [ä] e ⟨eŋg⟩ [ɛ] ɪ ⟨ɪpθ⟩ [ɪ] i ⟨idj⟩ [i] u ⟨uc⟩ [u] o ⟨oz⟩ [o̞] Sentences are written left-to-right, then top-to-bottom. Najan has no punctuation except spaces between words.
3.title: Orthography

4.body: Najan is a deterministic context-free language whose grammar can be expressed in extended Backus-Naur form as follows: clause ⇒ [ ⟨ mood ᴘᴛᴄʟ ⟩ ] ⟨ VP ⟩ verb phrase (VP) ⇒ [ ⟨ aspect ᴘᴛᴄʟ ⟩ ] ⟨ verb ⟩ | ⟨ stativized VP ⟩ | ⟨ ᴘʀᴇᴘ ⟩ ⟨ NP ⟩ ⟨ VP ⟩ | ⟨ ᴄᴏɴᴊ ⟩ ⟨ VP ⟩ ⟨ VP ⟩ stativized VP ⇒ "djʊ ⟨djʊ⟩" ⟨ VP ⟩ | "vʊ ⟨vʊ⟩" ⟨ ᴘʀᴇᴘ ⟩ ⟨ VP ⟩ noun phrase (NP) ⇒ ⟨ VP ⟩ | ⟨ ᴘʀᴏ ⟩ | ⟨ ᴅᴇᴛ phrase ⟩ | ⟨ quotation ⟩ | ⟨ ᴄᴏɴᴊ ⟩ ⟨ NP ⟩ ⟨ NP ⟩ ᴅᴇᴛ phrase ⇒ ⟨ ᴅᴇᴛ ⟩ [ ⟨ ᴘʀᴏ ⟩ ] ⟨ VP ⟩ quotation ⇒ "tca ⟨tca⟩" ⟨ quoted word ⟩ "tca ⟨tca⟩" quoted word ⇒ ⟨ word ⟩ - "tca ⟨tca⟩" - "tsa ⟨tsa⟩" | "tsa tca ⟨tsa tca⟩" | "tsa tsa ⟨tsa tsa⟩"
4.title: Syntax

6.breadcrumbs: Verb Phrases » Tense & Aspect » Tense & Aspect
6.title: Tense & Aspect

7.body: Arguments to a verb are expressed as case-marking prepositional phrases modifying the verb. As a result, arguments have no fixed order, and a single verb can take multiple arguments of the same semantic role. In the following, "you" and "I" are joint agents of the eating of a single orange: jecikocitorʊzarabʊmtcetjecikocitorʊzarabʊmtcetɪɴᴅᴀIᴀyouᴘanorangeeat“You and I are eating an orange.” We can usually reverse the order of the arguments without affecting the meaning: jerʊzarabʊmcikocitotcetjerʊzarabʊmcikocitotcetɪɴᴅᴘanorangeᴀIᴀyoueat“An orange is being eaten by you and me.” However, sometimes order does matter, for instance when universal and existential quantification are involved. In this example, the ball and glove are thrown as part of the same action: jerʊgiðazrʊgixovneθcikoθewisjerʊgiðazrʊgixovneθcikoθewisɪɴᴅᴘtheballᴘthegloveᴀIᴘғᴠthrow“I threw the ball and glove.” Since arguments are simply modifiers, they are not syntactically required and may be omitted if they can be inferred from context. When asked who I am, I could reply: jeŋɪkodjanʊθʊnjeŋɪkodjanʊθʊnɪɴᴅsʙᴊIJonathan“I am Jonathan.” Or, since "I" is the expected subject: jedjanʊθʊnjedjanʊθʊnɪɴᴅJonathan“[I] am Jonathan.”
7.title: Arguments

8.body: The particles vʊ ⟨vʊ⟩ and djʊ ⟨djʊ⟩ can be used to form a new stative verb phrase from another verb phrase. Stativization is especially useful when instantiating a verbal noun via a determiner phrase . Adding vʊ ⟨vʊ⟩ and a case-marking preposition before a verb phrase produces a new phrase meaning "to be a (case) with respect to (verb phrase)". A doctor (healer) is an agent of healing: vʊciflejvʊciflejsᴛᴀᴛᴀto heal“to be a healer” A sword is an instrument of fencing: vʊθlacesvʊθlacessᴛᴀᴛɪɴsto fence (engage in swordplay)“to be a sword” A child exists with respect to a mother: vʊqaθafvʊqaθafsᴛᴀᴛɢᴇɴto be a mother (of a child)“to be a child (of a mother)” The particle djʊ ⟨djʊ⟩ followed by a verb phrase means "to be an instance of (verb phrase)". A fire is an instance of burning: djʊtθocdjʊtθocsᴛᴀᴛto burn“to be a fire” Somone's happiness is an instance of being happy: djʊtayndjʊtaynsᴛᴀᴛto be happy“to be happiness”
8.title: Stativization

9.body: Any verb phrase can also function as a noun phrase, signifying an abstract state or action (e.g. "being human", "running", "love"). To talk about concrete instances, sets, or amounts of something (e.g. "you", "the victory", "two dogs", "some water", "several words"), we can use pronouns or determiner phrases.
9.title: Noun Phrases
